[3] Cholera - Nigeria
Date: Thu 2 Aug 2018
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/says-nigerian-cholera-outbreak-control-4-states-51765/


WHO says the cholera outbreak that has affected Nigeria since the beginning of the year [2018] is now under control in at least 4 of the 17 affected local government areas. In its latest epidemiological situation analysis, WHO said 367 new suspected cases and 4 deaths were reported in the Adamawa, Bauchi, Katsina, Niger, Plateau and Zamfara states in the week ending 15 Jul 2018.

"Samples collected from 12 of the cases tested positive by rapid diagnostic test (RDT). None of these have been cultured. As of 18 Jul 2018, a total of 16 892 suspected cases with 201 deaths (case fatality ratio 1.2 per cent) have been reported from Adamawa, Anambra, Bauchi, Borno, FCT, Gombe, Jigawa, Ebonyi, Kaduna, Kano, Katsina, Kogi, Nasarawa, Niger, Plateau, Yobe, and Zamfara since the beginning of 2018," WHO said.

To date, samples from 268 cases have tested positive for _Vibrio cholerae_ by culture. WHO noted that there has been an overall declining trend since the peak of the outbreak in the week ending 27 May 2018, when 1345 cases were reported. "With no new cases reported in the last 4 weeks in Anambra, Nasarawa, Borno, and Yobe States, the outbreak is considered to be under control in these states. The decrease in the number of cases has also been reported from Adamawa State, which has been one of the epi-centres of this outbreak. This is contributing to the overall declining trend across the country except in Zamfara and Katsina States, where the number of cases reported is still high," the epi-update said.

An estimated 72 per cent of the affected are aged 5 years and above. WHO also found males and females to be proportionally affected. The infected are being treated at specially designated health facilities that have cholera treatment center (CTC) support from Médicins Sans Frontières (MSF).

